==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bannan'' ‘curse, forbid’, from Indo-European ''*bha-'' ‘say’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[banna]], Old Saxon [[bannan#Old Saxon|bannan]] (Dutch [[bannen]]), Old High German [[bannan#Old High German|bannan]], Old Norse [[banna]] (Swedish [[banna]])

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[φάναι]], Latin [[fari]], [[fabula]], Slavic ''*bājō-'' (Russian [[баю]]), Armenian [[բառ]]

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈban:an/}}

===Verb===
'''bannan''' (class VII strong)
# to [[summon]], especially by proclamation
#:''Leode tosomne bannan'': to summon the people together.  (''Legend of St Andrew'')

